{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611614"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:12:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:12:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16231"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16231","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16231"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.05,0.1,0.5,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8922"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71218"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8922"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16231"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56692"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"7662"},{"type":"tags","id":"7691"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8144"},{"type":"tags","id":"8145"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21235"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21237"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71218"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA core needle biopsy is performed on an asymptomatic 45-year-old woman following an abnormal screening mammogram. Microscopic examination reveals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESmall, uniform cells with round nuclei\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECells filling and distending the terminal ductal lobular units\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPreserved lobular architecture\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELoosely cohesive cell pattern\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ENegative E-cadherin staining on immunohistochemistry\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely histological diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ductal carcinoma in situ","Fibroadenoma","Intraductal papilloma","Lobular carcinoma in situ","Sclerosing adenosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELobular carcinoma in situ\u003C/strong\u003E characteristically shows proliferation of small, uniform cells that fill and distend the terminal ductal lobular units while maintaining the overall lobular architecture. The key molecular feature is loss of E-cadherin expression, which results in the loosely cohesive nature of the cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect diagnoses can be excluded because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuctal carcinoma in situ\u003C/strong\u003E shows more cellular pleomorphism and maintains E-cadherin expression\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibroadenoma\u003C/strong\u003E demonstrates a biphasic pattern with both epithelial and stromal components\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntraductal papilloma\u003C/strong\u003E shows a branching fibrovascular core with epithelial proliferation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESclerosing adenosis\u003C/strong\u003E exhibits proliferation of both epithelial and myoepithelial components with preserved lobular architecture but lacks the characteristic cellular features described\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe loss of E-cadherin expression is particularly helpful in distinguishing lobular from ductal lesions, as it is a hallmark molecular feature of lobular neoplasia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Lobular carcinoma in situ shows small, uniform cells filling and distending the terminal ductal lobular units while maintaining lobular architecture.","E-cadherin loss is a characteristic molecular feature of lobular carcinoma in situ that helps distinguish it from ductal carcinoma in situ.","Lobular carcinoma in situ cells appear loosely cohesive due to loss of cell adhesion molecules."],"references":["\u0022Lobular carcinoma in situ\u0022 by Difu is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Lobular_carcinoma_in_situ.jpg","Wen HY, Brogi E. Lobular Carcinoma In Situ. Surg Pathol Clin. 2018 Mar;11(1):123-145. doi: 10.1016/j.path.2017.09.009. Epub 2017 Dec 8. PMID: 29413653; PMCID: PMC5841603.","Lee JY, Schizas M, Geyer FC, Selenica P, Piscuoglio S, Sakr RA, Ng CKY, Carniello JVS, Towers R, Giri DD, de Andrade VP, Papanastasiou AD, Viale A, Harris RS, Solit DB, Weigelt B, Reis-Filho JS, King TA. Lobular Carcinomas In Situ Display Intralesion Genetic Heterogeneity and Clonal Evolution in the Progression to Invasive Lobular Carcinoma. Clin Cancer Res. 2019 Jan 15;25(2):674-686. doi: 10.1158/1078-0432.CCR-18-1103. Epub 2018 Sep 5. PMID: 30185420; PMCID: PMC6726436.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56692"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16231"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21222"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21222","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21222"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dTz94idg2oeEbN5DcDmvblJCtDhngo.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dTz94idg2oeEbN5DcDmvblJCtDhngo.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1360,"height":1024}},{"type":"ite